    {
      "text": "A person died suddenly whose family is abroad. His viscera was preserved during autopsy. Which of the following can be detected in his visceral organs even on non-consumption before his death?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Morphine"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Aconite"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Arsenic"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Alcohol"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 3,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Option: D) Alcohol</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<p>In cases where the body is preserved, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f0705db1901692777187acdc0f9e24\">ethanol</span> can be detected in the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"93943f6ee2169277720298325fd255\">viscera</span> due to the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cc108d77f11692777202478d5c72bf\">fermentation</span> of body fluids and tissues. This post-mortem production of alcohol can make its <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"723fdec66b1692777186e92f0c6fdf\">detection</span> possible even if the person did not consume alcohol before death.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Morphine (Options A), Aconite (Option B), and Arsenic (Option C)</strong> can only be detected if they were consumed by the person</p>",
