      "explanation_audio_hin": null
    },
    {
      "text": "During autopsy of fetal death case, What is the order of examination to differentiate between live birth and stillbirth?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Abdomen> head> thorax"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Thorax> head> abdomen"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Head> abdomen> thorax"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Head> thorax> abdomen"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 2,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: D) Head > Thorax > Abdomen</strong></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p>During the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f0b5c46ede1692777182013e65115b\">autopsy</span> of a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f375a3584316927772020efa386e3e\">fetal</span> death case, the <strong>order of internal examination</strong> is critical for determining whether the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"421fecf0e21692777202704942ac48\">fetus</span> was <strong>stillborn or live-born</strong>. The standard and most logical approach is:</p>\n\n<p><strong>Head → Thorax → Abdomen</strong></p>\n\n<p>This sequence helps preserve important evidence:</p>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li>\n\t<p><strong>Head (first)</strong>:</p>\n\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>\n\t\t<p><strong>Intracranial haemorrhages</strong> or <strong>maceration changes</strong> may help estimate time of death.</p>\n\t\t</li>\n\t\t<li>\n\t\t<p>If the head is opened later, it may be distorted by loss of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"99a9bf133e1692777184ec4b1011fe\">cerebrospinal</span> fluid and pressure changes during thoracic/abdominal dissection.</p>\n\t\t</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p><strong>Thorax (second)</strong>:</p>\n\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>\n\t\t<p><strong>Hydrostatic test (lung float test)</strong> is crucial for determining <strong>live birth vs stillbirth</strong>.</p>\n\t\t</li>\n\t\t<li>\n\t\t<p>This test must be done <strong>before cutting major vessels</strong> to avoid artificial inflation of lungs.</p>\n\t\t</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p><strong>Abdomen (last)</strong>:</p>\n\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>\n\t\t<p>Examined after <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3c6021096816927772007954fcc158\">thoracic</span> cavity, especially to avoid <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5a50cd774d1692777186c56ec68eac\">displacement</span> of gas or fluids that can affect findings (e.g. <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"37863e7aec169277718310f33c6a11\">bowel</span> gas mimicking respiration).</p>\n\t\t</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ol>\n\n<table>\n\t<thead>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<th><strong>Step</strong></th>\n\t\t\t<th><strong>Purpose</strong></th>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</thead>\n\t<tbody>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td><strong>Head</strong></td>\n\t\t\t<td>Check for <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cd42e0ddad1692777190d18c595ec5\">intracranial</span> injuries, maceration, skull ossification</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td><strong>Thorax</strong></td>\n\t\t\t<td>Vital for <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"20b745c46c1692777189374f036950\">hydrostatic</span> lung test (float/sink test)</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td><strong>Abdomen</strong></td>\n\t\t\t<td>Check for organ development, meconium, and anomalies</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>",
