    {
      "text": "What is the specific name of the test performed by the doctor during the autopsy where they tied the bronchus and submerged the lung in water to determine if it floats or sinks?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Gettler's test"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Ploucquet's test"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Hydrostatic test"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Diatom's test"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 2,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: C) Hydrostatic test</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>The test described, where the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8c78ae88d11692777183752131dce3\">bronchus</span> is tied and the lung is immersed in water to check whether it floats or sinks, is known as the <strong>Hydrostatic test.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Hydrostatic test/ Raygat's test/ Breslau's 1 life test/ Lung floatation test</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>If the baby had respired, the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0dd428c12116927771819285c8849c\">alveoli</span> would be expanded/ dilated.</li>\n\t<li>Thus, as the lungs are expanded, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0dd428c12116927771819285c8849c\">alveoli</span> are dilated & the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8d3f700185169277719818b9ad28c8\">specific gravity</span> decreases.</li>\n\t<li>Alveoli are dilated d/t presence of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a459f313d9169277719789fdfb7ada\">residual</span> air.</li>\n\t<li>When lungs are expanded, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8d3f700185169277719818b9ad28c8\">specific gravity</span> becomes <1.</li>\n\t<li>Thus, they float when they are placed in the water</li>\n\t<li>This test is performed to assess the buoyancy of the lung, as the presence of air within the lung tissue causes it to float in water.</li>\n\t<li>It is used as a supportive indication of drowning, as <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5031a7245c1692777186f7e7aabc06\">drowning</span> often leads to the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"831d67ad8a1692777182763ca62e4b\">aspiration</span> of water into the lungs, resulting in increased lung buoyancy.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Incorrect Options:</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Gettler's test (Option A): </strong>It is based on the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f7dbd0ab551692777184f9b1a73c6d\">chloride</span> concentration in the blood samples of heart chambers. Normally, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f7dbd0ab551692777184f9b1a73c6d\">chloride</span> concentration in both right side chambers & left side chambers should be equal</p>\n\n<p><strong>Ploucquet's test (Option B): </strong>Plouquet's test is a test used to detect ratio between <strong>Weight of the lung to the Weight of the baby.</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Diatom's test (Option D): </strong>Diatom's test is a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d505e5aff31692777203af0565576c\">forensic</span> examination that involves analyzing the presence of diatoms, in various tissues and , fluids to determine if a person was submerged in water.</p>",
